WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.420
So I've been tasked with talking about assays and technologies for MRD with a focus on free

00:00:08.420 --> 00:00:14.980
nucleic acids. We heard a lot about MRD in the context of cellular disease detection for myeloma

00:00:14.980 --> 00:00:21.780
and leukemia. We'll change gears a little bit in the context of this lymphoma session, talk about

00:00:21.780 --> 00:00:32.800
DNA. These are my disclosures. So when we talk about MRD, I think we just

00:00:32.800 --> 00:00:38.640
have the operational definition. We're talking about a small volume of tumor cells remaining

00:00:38.640 --> 00:00:45.660
after treatment when we otherwise have no evidence of measurable disease. And we typically associate

00:00:45.660 --> 00:00:51.760
this with relapse risk, and we want a good way to measure this. In lymphomas, this concept

00:00:51.760 --> 00:00:59.040
is quite old, with even before the advent of the polymerase chain reaction, use of direct

00:00:59.040 --> 00:01:06.480
nucleic acid-based methods for in situ hybridization, and then later PCR, finding that we could detect

00:01:06.480 --> 00:01:14.240
and could monitor MRD. Though unfortunately, the sensitivity of these assays has

00:01:14.240 --> 00:01:21.740
not been borne out in terms of improving outcomes, for example, on follicle lymphoma, a randomized trial using MRD

00:01:21.740 --> 00:01:30.860
to inform therapy did not find the FOL12 Italian study an improvement in outcomes when using MRD to

00:01:30.860 --> 00:01:37.900
inform maintenance. So might we approach this a bit differently? And I think this graphic kind

00:01:37.900 --> 00:01:43.900
of gives us a sense for that. If we talk about a given blood vacutainer container,

00:01:45.660 --> 00:01:51.720
a vacutainer tube, and the number of molecules that we can interrogate in the blood from the

00:01:51.720 --> 00:01:58.320
leukocytes versus the plasma, we deal with several orders of magnitude different, a few million cells

00:01:58.320 --> 00:02:04.300
worth of DNA in the cellular fraction, and a few thousand cells worth of DNA in the acellular

00:02:04.300 --> 00:02:10.240
fraction. And we can tackle those million or thousand cells with different techniques.

00:02:11.020 --> 00:02:15.520
And I want to see if I can convince you that with a few thousand cells, you can achieve

00:02:15.520 --> 00:02:21.640
parts per million detection, as was alluded to earlier, with sensitive DNA methods.

00:02:21.700 --> 00:02:29.020
